1. Direct
This folder tracks my progress through The Programming Logic Workbook, a collection of 300+ structured exercises designed to build the mental foundation for DSA. Each gate covers a core thinking pattern — from decisions and loops to recursion and arrays. Solutions are written with clarity over cleverness. The goal is to think before typing.

2. Personal
I started this workbook because I realized I was memorizing code, not understanding logic. These 300 problems are my attempt to fix that — one gate at a time. Every solution here represents a concept I worked through from scratch, without shortcuts. This is where I build the foundation everything else stands on.

3. Philosophical
Programming is not about syntax — it is about decomposing a problem into steps small enough to execute. This workbook is a deliberate practice of that skill, repeated 300 times across six different domains of thinking. Logic built here transfers to every language, every framework, every system. The code is just the output; the thinking is the work.

4. Academic
As a BCA student preparing for advanced DSA coursework, I needed a structured way to strengthen problem-solving before jumping into data structures. This workbook provides exactly that — a progressive curriculum starting from boolean logic and building up to applied algorithmic thinking. Each gate is a checkpoint, not just a chapter.

5. Minimal
Three hundred problems. Six gates. Thirty days. This folder documents the work of building real logical thinking from the ground up — decisions, iterations, recursion, arrays, strings, and applied logic. No fluff, no shortcuts. Just the reps.
